 Traphagan develops data from Japan into a critical examination of how scholarly research in biomedical ethics, and ethics more generally, is conducted in North America. Arguing in a vein related to the emerging area of naturalized biomedical ethics, Traphagan proposes the creation of an empirically grounded study of moral behavior.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAutonomy (Psychology). 0aEthicsvCross-cultural studies. 0aMedical ethics. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Japanese Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438445540423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438445540/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles